sourceResource.description: Melanie Zwang Davis was born in Sennfeld, Germany, in 1891. Her uncle, Marcus Oppenheimer, immigrated to the United States and founded the town of Marcus, Washington.  Her father, Herman Zwang, joined her uncle in Marcus in 1871 but returned to Sennfeld in 1888 to marry Melanie’s mother.  The family immigrated Coleville, Washington, in 1897 and moved to Marcus in 1900.  She discusses life in Marcus and efforts by her family to preserve Jewish customs in the United States. sourceResource.description: In this interview Edith Horn describes her childhood in Nazi Germany and her family's escape to Cuba in 1939. She talks about their immigration to the United States later that year, the time they spent in Miami and New York, and her family’s eventual arrival in Seattle in 1940. In discussing her life in Seattle, Edith focuses on her school experiences at Temple de Hirsch during the Second World War and the process of joining Junior Hadassah. She describes her marriage to Werner Horn in 1952 at Herzl Synagogue and her involvement with groups including the Brandeis group of Hadassah, the Mount Scopus group, the Jewish Family Service, the Association for the Jewish Disabled, and Congregation Beth Shalom.  This accession is part of the Washington State Jewish Archives.

creator: Rosenbaum, Mildred
Goldberg, Eva
sourceResource.description: Eva Goldberg was born in Portland, Oregon, in 1913. She describes her family, the Charlets, and provides details about Jewish life in Centralia, Washington, where she grew up. Eva moved to Olympia after marrying Alan Goldberg, a son of Jacob Goldberg. She traces the Goldberg family’s move from North Dakota to Washington State and talks about the Jewish community in Olympia, the synagogue there, how observant Jews managed to get Kosher meat, and about Jewish education for the children. She discusses the Depression years and the anti-Semitic activities of the Silver Shirts, who had an encampment near Olympia. Eva also describes Jewish participation in Fort Lewis and at Evergreen College and relationships with the Jewish staff there. The interview concludes with a discussion of the family home on Hood Canal where the various Goldberg families would come during summer, for Passover, and other family events.  This accession is part of the Washington State Jewish Archives.

creator: Cordova, Fred
Greaves, Gary
sourceResource.description: Fred Cordova was a civic leader, activist, educator and a Filipino American icon. Born in Calfornia in 1931, he was adopted and raised in a family of migrant-contract-farmers. He moved to Seattle in 1948 to attend Seattle University. In 1957, Fred and his wife, Dorothy, co-founded the Filipino Youth Activities (FYA) of Seattle and created the award-winning FYA Drill Team in 1959. The FYA became an important force for organizing demonstrations in the 1960’s and 1970’s.The Cordovas also created the Demonstration Project for Asian Americans in the 1970’s, and the Filipino American National Historical Society in the 1980’s. In 1998, Seattle University awarded him an honorary doctorate for lifetime achievements in research, writing and promoting Filipino American history and community. He passed away in 2013.

Over his long career in Seattle journalism, he has worked at Seattle Magazine, The Seattle Times, KING-TV, and the Argus. He founded Seattle Weekly in 1976 and served as editor and publisher until 1997. He also started the Best Places, a guidebook series, which became Sasquatch Books. In 2007, he founded the online Northwest newspaper, Crosscut.

sourceResource.description: John Leonard Miller was born in Kentucky about 1889. He left home at the age of 12 and eventually worked in coal mining in Danville, Virginia where he joined the United Mine workers as an organizer. He worked as a harvester in the Midwest, then moved to Calgary, Canada where he joined the Socialist Party. Later returning to the U.S., he joined the Industrial Workers of the World in North Dakota. Miller was an informant for author Norman Clark and was involved in the "Everett Massacre." He used Jack Leonard as an alias. sourceResource.description: Audrey Gruger was a King County Council member and Washington State representative. After graduating from the University of Washington she became a social worker with the Washington Department of Social and Health Services. Eventually she felt she could be more effective as an elected official and in 1978 she was elected to the Washington State House of Representatives, after running a grass-roots campaign from her basement. She represented the 1st Legislative District in the Washington State House of Representatives from 1976 to 1981. She served on the King County Council from 1982-1993 and served as chair in 1986, 1992 and 1993. She passed away in 2010.

sourceResource.description: In this interview Annette Hyman Cohen discusses her years with the Seattle Section of the National Council of Jewish Women.  She describes her first Council meeting upon moving to Seattle in 1948, her Presidency beginning in 1953, and the work done by the Council of Jewish Women during her tenure as President.  Cohen talks about the nature of her administration and management of auxiliary programs, such as the Thrift Shop and the reading program, as well as her work on the bulletin.  This accession is part of the Washington State Jewish Archives.
